{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17414140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17414140"},"attributes":{"position":32,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T08:41:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T08:41:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11783"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474111"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:17:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:17:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11783"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"11783","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11783"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.08,0.36,0.09,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4397"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45341"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4397"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11783"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30254"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1519"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6221"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6225"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8973"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16078"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45341","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/45341"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA five-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his parents with a three-day history of episodic vomiting and watery diarrhoea. He had two episodes of vomiting and three episodes of diarrhoea the night prior to admission. This has been accompanied by a mild fever and poor oral intake. He last vomited 10 hours ago and there are no current ongoing fluid losses. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears lethargic but rousable. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 105/62 mmHg, respiratory rate 36/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. His mucous membranes are dry and capillary refill time is three seconds.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis medical record states that he weighed 12.5 kg last week. Currently he weighs 12.0 kg. The paediatric consultant advises to start prompt, but not rapid, nasogastric rehydration therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate rate for the nasogastric fluid regimen (maintenance and replacement)?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["66 mL/hr","21 mL/hr","45 mL/hr","86 mL/hr","120 mL/hr"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a case of dehydration likely due to gastroenteritis. It is important to assess dehydration status in patients presenting with poor oral intake associated with fluid loss. Commencement of rehydration therapy is common prior to further investigation if there are no suspected contraindications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn terms of route of administration, if the patient is tolerating enteral feeds, the \u003Cstrong\u003Eenteral route\u003C/strong\u003E should always be considered over IV. This is due to several benefits of the enteral route including fewer electrolyte disturbances, faster recovery rate, and the option of administering formula or additional nutritional regimens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFluid requirements in children can be calculated using the following formula:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETotal fluid requirement =\u003C/strong\u003E Maintenance + Replacement of deficit + Replacement of ongoing losses\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaintenance fluid calculation:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Holliday-Segar method (4:2:1 rule) is a useful tool to calculate maintenance fluid requirements (per hour). Give 4 mL/kg/hr for the first 10 kg, 2 mL/kg/hr for the next 10 kg, and 1 mL/kg/hr for each kg over 20 kg. It is important to use the patient\u0027s pre-morbid weight. In this case, the child\u0027s pre-morbid weight was 12.5 kg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore, \u003Cstrong\u003Emaintenance fluid = (4 x 10) + (2 x 2.5) mL/hr = 45 mL/hr\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReplacement fluid calculation:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most accurate way to calculate fluid deficit in a dehydrated patient is by using the patient\u0027s weight:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeficit (mL) =\u003C/strong\u003E [Patient\u0027s pre-morbid weight - Patient\u0027s current weight] x 1000\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the \u003Cstrong\u003Edeficit = (12.5 - 12.0) x 1000 = 500 mL\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E500 mL/24 hours =\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003E21 mL/hr\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReplacement of ongoing losses:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is also important to replace ongoing fluid losses in patients with ongoing symptoms. The most accurate way to do this is by measuring their fluid losses. As this patient has no current ongoing losses and is only mildly dehydrated, replacement of ongoing losses is unnecessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFollowing the formula above, the total fluid requirement for this patient:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E45 mL/hr + 21 mL/hr = 66 mL/hr\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor the enteral route, the recommended type of fluid in patients without metabolic derangement is oral rehydration solution.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Fluid deficit calculation = [pre-morbid weight (kg) - current weight (kg)] x 1000","Total fluid requirements = fluid maintenance + replacement of deficit + ongoing losses","Use the 4:2:1 rule to calculate maintenance fluid requirements."],"references":["Department for Health and Wellbeing, Government of South Australia. Intravenous Fluid (IV) Management in Children. South Australian Paediatric Clinical Practice Guidelines. Retrieved from: https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/fbce826b-e137-4716-a2c0-72c7e70a0e3c/Intravenous+%28IV%29+Fluid+Management+in+Children_Paed_v1_0.pdf?MOD=AJPERES\u0026CACHEID=ROOTWORKSPACE-fbce826b-e137-4716-a2c0-72c7e70a0e3c-nSSNI4k (Viewed 26 May 2022)","The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Nasogastric Fluids. Clinical practice guidelines. Retrieved from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Nasogastric_Fluids/ (Viewed 26 May 2022)","The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Intravenous Fluids. Clinical practice guidelines. Retrieved from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Intravenous_Fluids/ (Viewed 26 May 2022)"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30254"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11783"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/30254"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-13T18:30:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-13T18:30:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4397"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45341"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interp